title: Study of the 6Li+16O light heavy-ion system around the Coulomb barrier.

x4freetext: Study of the 6Li+16O light heavy-ion system around the
Coulomb barrier.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.452, p.150 (1986)

x4freetext: 4 MV Dynamitron Tandem accelerator.
6Li beam.
Energy was up to 150 particle-nA. With the help of a
set of collimators the beam spot on the target was
focused to about 2.5 mm diameter.
25 mu-g/cm2 thin self-supporting SiO2 target of natural
isotopic composition was mounted in the center of a 42
cm diameter scattering chamber.
Six detectors of nominal thickness 1.0-3.0 mm,
each subtending a solid angle of about 1 msr were used.
Faraday cup was used. Secondary-electron emission was
suppressed be a coper ring biased to -400 V in front of
the cup, thus enabling the collected charge to be
measured with an error of about 3%.
Beam reaching the cup had to be determined for
each bombarding energy by comparison of the beam
current with and without hitting the target. This
procedure introduced an additional error of 4%.
Thin (10-20 microns) Al foils were placed in front of
the forward-angle detectors in order to stop
elastically scatered 6Li ions.
Total cross sections were deduced by analysing the
proton angular distributions in terms of a Legendre
polynominal expansion.

x4freetext: 6Li2+ beam passed through a liquid-nitrogen trap.
6Li+3 charge state was used to maintain reasonable
beam for energies in excess of 8 MeV.
100 mu-g/cm2 MoO3 layer evaporated on 0.1 mm thick,
air-cooled Ta backing was used.The target thickness
corresponds to an energy loss of the Li6 ions of 160
(70) keV at ELi=4(12) MeV.
120 cm3 detector of 1.95 keV resolution at
E gamma = 1.33 MeV was placed at a distance of 85 mm
from the target.
